article.headline: Rockets center held to 10 points in 22 minutes
article.linkText: Bucks buckle down on Yao in win over Rockets
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Searching for a spark to turn around their season, the Milwaukee Bucks hope they found it Tuesday night with a 28-point win over the Houston Rockets. Michael Redd scored 28 points and Desmond Mason added 24 to lead the Bucks past Houston 115-87. It was Milwaukee's second straight win, only the second this season the Bucks have had a two-game winning streak. "I've been saying all year that if we can get a convincing win, it can get us turned around and give us some confidence," said Mason, who scored 14 points in the first quarter. "This is the first step toward a good winning streak. We've got two now and we've got to get greedy and get some more." Mason said the win was the best the Bucks had played all season. "We had a killer instinct tonight," he said. "We got them down and stayed on top of them." Redd said the win could have a snowball effect for the Bucks, who play their next four games on the road. "We never lost our confidence, but we are starting to play well and come together as a team," Redd said. Marcus Fizer added 15 points and seven rebounds for Milwaukee. The 115 points was the most the Bucks have scored this season, topping their 110 points in a double-overtime loss to Miami on Nov. 14. Tracy McGrady led Houston with 20 points on 7-of-19 shooting, while Bob Sura added 19 points and six assists. The Bucks limited Rockets center Yao Ming to 10 points and three rebounds in 22 minutes. "Our big guys really did a good job tonight," Redd said. The Bucks used a 17-4 run to start the third quarter to take a 77-47 lead on Redd's 3-pointer. Mason and Redd scored 15 points during the run and ended up accounting for 23 of the Bucks' 30 third-quarter points. Mo Williams' driving layup and free throw with 1.1 seconds left in the quarter gave the Bucks a 90-59 lead. The Rockets never got closer than 25 in the fourth quarter. Rockets coach Jeff Van Gundy said his team was outplayed in every phase of the game. "We got hammered on the boards, hammered in transition and hammered off the dribble," he said. "This is not the first time this has happened this season." Ming said most of Houston's trouble was caused by mental lapses. "We (were) just not ready to play tonight," he said. "They scored a lot in transition and second chances. If you give them those, you can't win." Milwaukee used a 20-10 run at the end of the first quarter to grab a 37-25 lead. Mason had six points during the run and finished with 14 points in the first quarter. The Bucks went on a 20-5 run in the second quarter and took a 57-32 lead when Zaza Pachulia grabbed a rebound off a missed free throw and scored with 1:23 remaining. Milwaukee held Houston to just five points over the first 10 minutes of the second quarter.

Game notes
The Bucks placed F Keith Van Horn on the injured list due to right ankle tendinitis. Van Horn, averaging 17.2 points and 8.2 rebounds, has missed the last 10 games with the injury. ... Rockets G David Wesley, acquired in a trade Monday from New Orleans for Jim Jackson and Bostjan Nachbar, was not with the team. ... Bucks F Joe Smith left the game midway through the third quarter with left groin strain and did not return.
